## Why two licences

CC-BY 4.0 is the appropriate licence for normative documents: it preserves authorship attribution while permitting unrestricted adoption, including by commercial competitors. It is the de facto licence for open specifications across the web (used by Schema.org, the W3C for many deliverables, and most modern RFC-style publications).

MIT is the appropriate licence for code: it permits embedding in proprietary products with minimal compliance overhead, which is the standard expectation for validator libraries and reference tooling.

The two licences are fully compatible. A downstream product implementing the MakeitSEO Standard typically incorporates CC-BY 4.0 specification material (cited with attribution) and MIT-licensed validator code (with notice). No file in this repository uses a copyleft licence; nothing here will require derivative works to adopt any particular licence of their own.

